  <entry>
    <id>2</id>
    <title>Combined summary - State of the transaction privacy work in Bitcoin</title>
    <updated>2026-07-07T04:54:59.349209+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://delvingbitcoin.org/t/state-of-the-transaction-privacy-work-in-bitcoin/2622/28" rel="alternate"/>
    <published>2026-06-18 21:27:51.340000+00:00</published>
    <summary>The realm of Bitcoin privacy is witnessing nuanced advancements primarily through mechanisms outside the core protocol layer, including sidechains and wallet integrations. Technologies like Confidential Transactions are being incorporated into sidechains, while innovations such as Silent Payments, PayJoin, and CoinJoin are integrated directly within wallets. This strategic shift underscores a broader inclination towards enhancing privacy without altering the foundational blockchain protocol. The introduction of Cross-Input Signature Aggregation (CISA) could potentially lower the cost of solutions like CoinJoin, although it doesn't inherently boost privacy. These developments reflect a trend towards optimizing existing measures rather than implementing radical changes at the protocol level. Regulatory considerations and the complexity of modifying the core protocol contribute to this focus, alongside the need to uphold transparency and a verifiable fixed supply.
Furthermore, the Lightning Network's popularity, known for its scalability and a degree of privacy, has lessened the urgency for direct privacy enhancements at Layer 1. This suggests an overarching movement in Bitcoin privacy that leans towards solutions aligning with regulatory frameworks and not requiring fundamental changes to the protocol itself. Despite the evolution of wallet-layer enhancements, there remains a notable gap at the protocol level that technologies like CISA could address.
CoinSwap is another innovative protocol aimed at enhancing on-chain privacy for cryptocurrency transactions. Active implementations and ongoing developments of CoinSwap can be explored through various resources. Interested individuals can delve into detailed explanations and the progress of CoinSwap through key URLs such as [Developing Advancements in Onchain Privacy](https://opensats.org/blog/developing-advancements-in-onchain-privacy) and [CoinSwap Topics](https://opensats.org/topics/coinswap). The Citadel technology team plays a significant role in this, with their contributions accessible via their GitHub repository at [Citadel Tech's CoinSwap](https://github.com/citadel-tech/coinswap) and [Protocol Specification](https://github.com/citadel-tech/Coinswap-Protocol-Specification). Additional insights into protocol discussions are available on forums like BitcoinTalk, specifically in the thread titled [BitcoinTalk CoinSwap Discussion](https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=321228.0).
In summary, while new technologies continue to emerge and evolve, the landscape of Bitcoin privacy favors implementations that enhance user experience and integration ease over complete overhauls of foundational elements. This strategic prioritization helps maintain compatibility with existing systems and regulatory standards, thereby facilitating a more widespread adoption and practical application of privacy-enhancing technologies in the cryptocurrency space.</summary>
